Overall, this looks like normal session lifecycle transitions with no new failures or blockers emerging. Since the system is stable and the only state change is that session completion, I should report this as a minimal update to the group.\\n\\nLooking back at the earlier reports though, I notice the Lead direct session shows endedAt 13:15 UTC but the 14:05 UTC report indicated it was still active and receiving messages—there's a discrepancy in the timestamps I need to reconcile.\\n\\nChecking the actual session data more carefully: the direct session ended at 13:15 UTC (timestamp 1776162158012), which is after the heartbeat state's lastSeen of 13:36 UTC. The session's last message was a 13:00 UTC heartbeat that timed out waiting for a response, even though the session had already been marked as done in the heartbeat state. So it appears the heartbeat state is tracking the session as done, which aligns with the current status.\\n\\nLooking at the session history, the Lead direct session actually shows two heartbeats at 13:56 and 14:01 UTC in the messages, but the session status is marked as \\\"done\\\"—suggesting these messages were delivered as inter-session notifications rather than through a running session. Comparing the current 14:06 UTC state against the baseline from 13:36 UTC, the direct session was already marked done in the baseline, so this isn't a new change.\\n\\nSince the heartbeat state at 13:36 already had the session as done, and the current sessions list shows the same done status, there's no state change to report—the cron job at 13:56 appears to have used a different delivery mechanism rather than spawning a new running session. Based on the sessions list timestamp comparison, the lead direct session appears to be done in both the current and baseline snapshots, so there's no state change to report—I'll stay silent and exit.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"Comparing current sessions